The optical properties of FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs were studied using UV–Vis absorption spectroscopy and fluorescence spectroscopy. The UV–Vis absorption spectrum of FCW-CDs ( Fig. 5a ) exhibits a broad absorption band with a maximum at 293 nm, extending up to 450 nm. This absorption feature is attributed to π–π* transitions in CC bonds and n–π* transitions in CO bonds (Kanwal et al., 2022). The FCW-CDs solution appears yellow under daylight and exhibits bright blue fluorescence under UV irradiation, as shown in the inset of Fig. 5a. The fluorescence emission spectrum of FCW-CDs ( Fig. 5a) reveals a broad emission band centered at 445 nm when excited at 370 nm. The fluorescence emission spectra of FCW-CDs (Fig. 6a) were recorded at excitation wavelengths ranging from 280 nm to 410 nm in 10 nm increments. The emission maxima remained nearly constant across different excitation wavelengths, indicating that FCW-CDs exhibits minimal excitation-dependent shifts. The fluorescence quantum yield of FCW-CDs was determined to be 33 % using quinine sulfate as a reference. Furthermore, the fluorescence lifetime of FCW-CDs was measured using the time-correlated single-photon counting (TCSPC) technique, yielding an average lifetime of 5.51 ns ( Fig. 7
). Similarly, the UV–Vis absorption spectrum of NFCW-CDs ( Fig. 5b) exhibits an absorption band with a maximum at 300 nm, extending up to 500 nm. The fluorescence emission spectrum of NFCW-CDs ( Fig. 5b) shows a broad emission peak at 455 nm when excited at 370 nm. The fluorescence emission spectra of NFCW-CDs ( Fig. 6b) were obtained using excitation wavelengths from 280 nm to 410 nm in 10 nm increments. The emission maxima exhibited negligible shifts across different excitation wavelengths, suggesting that NFCW-CDs display minimal excitation-dependent variations. The fluorescence quantum yield of NFCW-CDs was found to be 12.1 %. To evaluate FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs effiency, the quantum yield values were compared with those reported in other studies ( Table 1
), particularly those using coconut water as carbon precursor. The results indicate that FCW-CDs possess superior fluorescence characteristics, making it a promising candidate for potential optical applications.

High-resolution transmission electron microscopy (HR-TEM) was employed to examine the morphology and size of the FCW-CDs. HR-TEM analysis (
                     Fig. 8a
                     ) revealed that FCW-CDs exhibited a spherical morphology with particle sizes predominantly below 10 nm. Fig. 8b shows a single particle with fringes, which are indicative of the partially crystalline nature of FCW-CDs. The “d” spacing value was identified as 0.264 nm and assigned to the in-plane lattice spacing of aromatic carbon or graphene-like structures consistent with previous reports (Kanwal et al., 2022). The inset of Fig. 8b depicts the selected area electron diffraction (SAED) pattern of FCW-CDs, which further reinforces the partially crystalline nature of the FCW-CDs.

The antioxidant properties of FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs were analyzed by modified ferric ion reducing antioxidant power (FRAP) assay. The capacity of FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs to reduce ferric ions was compared to that of ascorbic acid, a well-known antioxidant used as a positive reference (
                     Fig. 9a
                     ). Various concentrations of FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs were separately subjected to ferric ion reduction and the absorption was monitored at 700 nm (
                     Table 2

                     ). It was found that the absorbance at 700 nm increases with the concentration of FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs. This concentration-dependent increase in absorption indicates enhanced inhibition activity of FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs (
                     Table 2
                     ). The percentage inhibition of ferric ion reduction by FCW-CDs increased from 3.2 % at 5 μg/mL to 44.44 % at 20 μg/mL (
                     Fig. 9b), while NFCW-CDs increased from 33.33 % at 5 μg/mL to 41.17 % at 20 μg/mL (
                     Fig. 9c & 
                     Table 3

                     ). The IC50 value, which represents the half-maximal inhibitory concentration, was 22.00 μg/mL for FCW-CDs, 36.70 μg/mL for NFCW-CDs and 13.61 μg/mL for ascorbic acid (
                     Table 4

                     ). The lower the IC50 value, the higher its antioxidant potential will be. Notably, the FCW-CDs exhibited an IC50 value comparable to the positive control ascorbic acid. Meanwhile, NFCW-CDs showed significantly lower antioxidant activity compared to FCW-CDs, revealing a higher reducing potential in fermented coconut water carbon dots compared to non-fermented coconut water carbon dots. Interestingly, the dual function of these carbon dots as both antioxidants and prooxidants was observed, as illustrated in Fig. 10
                     . Carbon dots act as prooxidants in visible light by generating reactive oxygen species (ROS); they also exhibited strong antioxidant properties under normal conditions, scavenging free radicals (Innocenzi and Stagi, 2023) and reducing ferric ions. This balance between antioxidant and prooxidant activity suggests their potential for controlled biomedical applications.

The antibacterial properties of FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs were studied using the disc diffusion method, investigating the effect of CDs on the growth of Klebsiella pneumoniae (Gram-negative bacteria) and Staphylococcus aureus (Gram-positive bacteria) under light exposure. Control plates treated with 20 μL of solvent showed no inhibitory activity, as no zone of inhibition (ZOI) was recorded. In contrast, filter papers treated with FCW-CDs at different concentrations (5 μL, 10 μL, and 15 μL) exhibited inhibition zones. Notably, 15 μL of FCW-CDs produced a 11 mm ZOI against K. pneumoniae ( Fig. 11
& Table 5
). For S. aureus, the control plates similarly showed no inhibitory activity. However, FCW-CDs treated filter papers demonstrated antimicrobial effects, with 10 μL and 15 μL producing inhibition zones of 8 mm and 12 mm, respectively. Similarly NFCW-CDs control plates treated with 20 μL of solvent showed no inhibitory activity. However, filter papers soaked in NFCW-CDs at varying concentrations (5 μL, 10 μL, and 15 μL) exhibited no inhibition zones against Klebsiella pneumoniae ( Fig. 12
& Table 6
). Significantly, filter papers treated with 15 μL of NFCW-CDs showed a 6 mm inhibition zone against S. aureus. These findings highlight that the antibacterial effectiveness of both FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs is dependent on dosage, with higher concentrations leading to more pronounced antimicrobial effects, particularly effective against K. pneumoniae and S. aureus (Gedda et al., 2023; Liang et al., 2021). However, FCW-CDs consistently exhibited larger ZOI values than NFCW-CDs at all concentrations, suggesting their superior antibacterial activity. This difference is primarily attributed to ROS (Reactive oxygen species) production under light exposure, where FCW-CDs may generate a higher amount of ROS, leading to increased oxidative stress, membrane damage, and bacterial cell death, whereas NFCW-CDs produce lower ROS level, resulting in weaker antibacterial effects. The ROS production and interaction of CDs to bacterial surfaces are depicted in Fig. 13 . Both CDs possess hydrophobic surface modification with hydrogel, facilitating bacterial adhesion and ROS penetration, (Li et al., 2022) but FCW-CDs demonstrate superior efficacy due to their higher ROS yield and stronger photodynamic antibacterial activity. A comparative analysis with chitosan and silver nano particles ( Table 7
) further emphasizes that while silver nanoparticles exhibit strong antibacterial properties, their cytotoxicity is concern; whereas chitosan shows moderate antibacterial effects but lacks a ROS-mediated killing mechanism. Compared to NFCW-CDs, FCW-CDs exhibits superior antibacterial properties due to its higher ROS generation and enhanced photo responsive antibacterial action, making it a more promising and effective alternative for bacterial inhibition.

The cytotoxicity of carbon dots obtained from fermented and non-fermented coconut water on DLA cells was evaluated by trypan blue exclusion method. The percentage cell viability of cell lines were assessed by treating cells with varying concentrations of FCW-CDs, NFCW-CDs and staining with trypan blue dye. The viable cells repel the dye, but non-viable cells absorb the dye and thus turn blue in color. Both NFCW-CDs and FCW-CDs exhibited concentration-dependent in vitro cytotoxic activity against DLA cell lines. At a concentration of 2.5 μL/mL, FCW-CDs induced only 3.77 % cell death, while a higher concentration of 50 μL/mL resulted in 25 % cell death ( Fig. 14
a). In contrast, carbon dots from non-fermented coconut water showed lower cytotoxic effect, with 3.77 % cell death at 2.5 μL/mL and 17.2 % at 50 μL/mL ( Fig. 14b). These findings suggest that fermentation enhances anticancer efficacy of carbon dots. The dose-dependent cytotoxic effects might be attributed to higher reactive oxygen species (ROS) production, as illustrated in the schematic representation ( Fig. 15
). The interaction between carbon dots and cancer cells presumably generates oxidative stress, resulting to cellular apoptosis (Jia et al., 2020).

The effect of biosynthesized CDs at concentrations ranging from 100 μL to 500 μL on mitosis was investigated using fresh bulbs of Allium cepa L. The antimitotic activity of CDs was assessed by adding various concentrations of FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs in comparison with a control (distilled water). The mitotic Index (MI) was calculated to quantify the effect of CDs on cell division. The Mitotic Index increased with the concentration of carbon dots, similar to the control, indicating potential biocompatibility in plant cells ( Tables 8 & 9
). The cells shown in Fig. 16
(A, C, E), the control (distilled water) treatment on Allium cepa cells exhibited no chromosomal aberrations, indicating normal cellular division under standard conditions. Similarly, in Fig. 16 (B, D, F), treatment with FCW-CDs also showed no chromosomal aberrations. However, in Fig. 17
(A, C, E), the control (distilled water) again displayed normal cell division, whereas in Fig. 17 (B, D, F), treatment with NFCW-CDs resulted in only negligible chromosomal aberrations. Furthermore, a schematic representation ( Fig. 18
) illustrates the normal process of cell division from a parent cell to two daughter cells, (Behrouzi et al., 2022) demonstrating that onion bulbs exposed to CDs likely absorbed them into their roots and tissues, with no observed genotoxic or mitodepressive effects. Therefore, these FCW-CDs and NFCW-CDs, if released into the environment, are unlikely to harm plants, suggesting biocompatibility.
